## Configure OpenClaw to Use oMLX

oMLX is **OpenAI-compatible** (`POST /v1/chat/completions`), so OpenClaw connects as a standard provider.

### Step 1: Edit OpenClaw Config

Run `openclaw config edit` and add oMLX as a provider:

```json
{
  "models": {
    "providers": {
      "omlx": {
        "baseUrl": "http://localhost:8000/v1",
        "apiKey": "omlx-local",
        "api": "openai-completions",
        "models": [
          {
            "id": "Qwen3-4B-MLX-4bit",
            "name": "Qwen3 4B (oMLX Local)"
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  }
}
```

> **Tip:** The `id` must match the exact model name shown in `http://localhost:8000/v1/models`. Check the oMLX admin panel or run `curl http://localhost:8000/v1/models` to see available models.

### Step 2: Use the Model

In OpenClaw, set your model to `omlx/Qwen3-4B-MLX-4bit` (provider/model format).

### Why oMLX Matters for OpenClaw Agents

OpenClaw agents make **dozens of tool calls per task**. Each tool call re-processes the full system prompt (20K+ tokens). Without prefix caching, that's a 20-30 second wait *every single time*.

With oMLX's **tiered KV cache**, the system prompt prefix is cached in RAM after the first call. All subsequent calls skip prefill and complete in seconds. Multiple agents even **share** the same prefix cache via paged attention — like vLLM in production, but on your Mac.
